          >spencer@spencer.place</span
        > or <a href="/collab">learn more</a>.
      </p>

      <h4 class="font-bold mb-2">
        some questions & some ever-evolving answers
      </h4>
      <div class="flex flex-col gap-2 pb-8 text-base">
        <details>
          <summary class="text-lg"> 1. why the internet? </summary>
          <p>
            Growing up, I never felt like I fit in at school or local
            communities. Instead, I grew up on the internet. The internet was
            where I found my community, learned what it meant to have a passion,
            and discovered the range of humanity—how tender and how heartless
            people could be.
          </p>
          <p>
            Because of this, I am driven to understand and create spaces that
            allow for people to be seen: their lives, sorrows, and dreams. The
            internet is increasingly the medium for this, from our constant
            encounters with the supercomputers in our pockets to the pleas to be
            seen in every comment and corner of the web. Grappling directly with
            the tension between the oppressive bases of technology and its role
            as a global source for connection, meaning, and agency, my work
            speculates what the internet might look like if these were in
            harmony by offering living systems that do so. Varying between
            spaces that invite new ways for seeing each other digitally, tools
            for creating new methods of connection, and objects that inspire
            whimsical intimacy with our devices, I am always in search of a form
            of technology that lives as we do.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary class="text-lg"> 2. what is your goal? </summary>
          <p>
            That we live in a world where the technology we make and advance
            feels as fundamentally human as humanities or cultural work. That we
            live in a world where we aren't trying to get away from our phones
            and remove technology, where our idea of technology is not so
            dominated by capitalism and surveillance, where it can be used for
            fun things, poetic things, things that have no reason for existing
            other than the fact that someone wanted them to. A world where
            technology is as natural a medium for bringing us closer together as
            public space is.
          </p>
          <p>
            In practical terms, I'm still not really sure what the end steady
            state of this work looks like, but I have inspirations: Noguchi,
            Fluxus, MSCHF, Bluesky. A full-time artist <Footnote
